post_text:
The Riggs Performer of the Week/Fine Arts student of the Week is:

Braedon Cunningham

After 6 months of no band, freshman Braedon hit the ground running at the high school. He has already shown his dedication to the program by being a member of marching band and signing up for Jazz Band. He is always on time, always on task, and is quick to pick up new concepts. In the first two weeks of school, he has shown up for more voluntary lessons than anyone else, and has a clear goal in mind of what he would like to accomplish with his instrument. He has already impressed the student leaders and myself with his commitment and willingness to learn.

Congratulations Braedon!

Today is our first pep band of the year and we are SO EXCITED!!

The athletic office has supplied us with enough bleachers that we can distance, and Mrs. MJ has been hard at work sewing bell covers for brass instruments!

Usually we would invite former students to join us whenever they are able, but due to health concerns and especially since Hughes county has gone to "substantial community spread", only current band members will be able to play with the pep band at this time.

Should anything change, we can't wait to have you join us once again! Stay safe, stay sane, stay healthy.... and Go Govs!

Final day of marching before school starts! It was a four hour grind in the HEAT but the emerald regiment did an insanely efficient job and has learned 3 of 4 songs ... in less than 6 hours as a full group. Pretty incredible if you ask me.

Today also consisted of some bonding time during our shade breaks, and the baritones getting to show off their new bell covers!

Edited to add: the group activity was for less than 15 minutes, as per CDC ‚Äúclose contact‚Äù specifications.

We are proud to announce our Drum Major for the 2020-2021 school year: Mesa Winder!

Mesa has been an integral member of the Riggs Band since joining her freshman year. She has been in varying jazz bands - switching saxophones as needed - and marching band. She has also participated in Contest every year, attended numerous honor bands, served as section leader, and is a member of the Tri-M Music Honor Society.

Under her leadership, we will have a very successful season!

Jasmine Rounds

Jasmine has played flute for the Riggs Band for four years. She picked up trumpet this year and joined Jazz Lab, has been a member of the marching band for three years, and served as the Emerald Regiment's drum major this year.

post_text:
Thank you to our administration for their communication and great care for their students and staff.
This means the band will NOT be traveling to Region Large Group contest Wednesday or the State Basketball Tournament Friday, nor will the Drumline be performing at the same event.
Although this is a disappointment because of the hard work students have put forth in preparing, it is about the PROCESS of the preparation that makes us better people, and it is about the SAFETY of our students and those in our community that matters above all. Maybe we can find a time after April 1 to have a small performance to showcase the work the students have done. In the meantime: Stay healthy, all!

shared_text:
Pierre Governor Gymnastics
December 2, 2019 at 9:34 AM ¬∑

Governor Gymnastics Senior Spotlight

Jasmine Rounds | Senior

Favorite event to compete is Beam

Favorite meet snack is Puppy chow or cheezits

Favorite memory is Team day at state 2019 when all 5 competing girls stuck their beam routines. I wasn't competing, but it was really cool to be a part of the team when it happened and to be cheering on each girl as they went.

Something that might surprise you about me is I actually don't like naps. I feel more tired after taking one than when I was first awake.

Planning to attend SDSU and major in pre-med human biology and do Air Force ROTC

I would travel to Paris. I've always wanted to go there.

My favorite athlete is Simone Biles

The best advice I can give future gymnasts is to make friends with the girls on the team. Not knowing anyone could make practice less enjoyable to go to, so make friends and just have fun.

post_text:
Congratulations to these students for their acceptance into the 62nd Augustana Band Festival! The festival will take place November 8-9 on the Augustana University campus, with the Grand Finale concert taking place at the Washington Pavilion on November 9 at 6:30pm. We have one driver and could still use one more!

The Pride of the Dakotas needs you! We are looking for two volunteers willing to donate their time, pickup, and gas to pull our equipment trailers to Minneapolis this weekend as we are performing at the Youth in Music Marching Band Championships. Here are the particulars:

We have one 28ft trailer and one 16ft trailer. It'd probably be best if the 28ft is pulled with a 3/4 or 1 ton pickup. The 16ft can pretty easily be towed with a 1/2 ton pickup. We would load up at 6:45am and depart Brookings at 7:15am Saturday October 12th. We will travel to downtown Minneapolis to US Bank Stadium. We would stay overnight in Minneapolis, OR you‚Ä¶ More

post_text: If you are in the RC area this week... swing by! What an awesome opportunity!
shared_text:
Rapid City Stevens HS Band
July 8, 2019 at 11:05 AM ¬∑

This Thursday we have a unique and exciting opportunity in Rapid City, SD. The Cadets Drum and Bugle Corps from Allentown, PA will be in town for a rehearsal day on their travels between DCI competitions. Their rehearsals are open to the public, so this is an opportunity to watch a world-class drum corps at work. They will be at O'Harra Stadium at SDSM&T rehearsing from around 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. with more complete run-throughs happening in the mid to late afternoon. Swing by the field and see an elite group of musicians do what it takes to be one of the best.

Airmen of Note
March 1, 2019 at 10:00 AM ¬∑

Major Glenn Miller was born on this day in 1904! This year also marks the 75th anniversary of his death while serving in the Army Air Corps during WWII. Chief Master Sgt. Kevin Burns, who continues the tradition of leadership passed down from Miller, visited his memorial stone at Arlington National Cemetery to pay respects on behalf of the Airmen of Note. (Videography by MSgt Grant Langford)
Glenn Miller Birthplace Society & Museum

shared_text:
The Instrumentalist Magazine
February 5, 2019 at 3:07 PM ¬∑

"Valuing students extends to the whole student; they are valuable as people, not just because we need them in the band. Some students have problems with their grades in other classes, so we have tutorials for them. They know we are taking an interest in the total person not just how they perform in band. The things they learn by being a member of the band program will help them function in college and on their job once they leave us. We want our kids to be successful in life." Gloria Ramirez, April 2017
